10 quodque· · · debeat i. e. And though these abuses are such, as one should scarcely permit even to be heard, yet very many actu- ally boast that. On this consecutive subjunctive, cp. Ki'ihner II p. 855 f. and Peter ad loc.

Debeat is the reading of all our MSS„ which we have no right to emend, unless it can be shown to be untenable. Nevertheless John, although forced to admit that ‘debeat’ is possible, is at great pains to show that ‘debebat,' an emendation of Muretus, ought to be substituted. But even granting that the imperfect ind. like ἔδει, ἐξῆν in Greek, may express unreality in the present, John's view involves the further necessity of taking ‘quod . . . debeat' as the object of ‘iactans,' the infinitives becom- ing epexegetic, a far-fetched and unnatural construction. Finally, if Mes— salla, as John contends, wished to express his emphatic condemnation of the practices in question with the implied regret that they had, up to his time. passed without deserving censure, vix would also be out of place.
